def: A comprehensive group equivalent to the true Coelenterata,i.e., exclusive of the sponges. They are so named from presence ofstinging cells (cnidae) in the tissues. See Coelenterata.
Native simplicity; unaffected plainness or ingenuousness;artlessness.A story which pleases me by its naïveté -- that is, by itsunconscious ingenuousness. De Quincey.
To take out from a tomb; a disinter.
Pertaining to a dunghill; hence, mean; dirty; paltry. [Obs.]Howell.
Relating or tending to discontent. [R.] "Pride is everdiscontentive." Feltham.
The act of smearing or covering with wax. B. Jonson.
A fish (Coregonus ferus) of North Wales and Northern Europe,allied to the lake whitefish; -- called also powan, and schelly.[Written also gwyniad, guiniad, gurniad.]
To convert into, or to impregnate with, sugar.
The operation of dividing the navel-string.
A meadow.A mede All full of freshe flowers, white and reede. Chaucer.To fertile vales and dewy meads My weary, wandering steps he leads.Addison.
Tender; soft; nice; -- now only used in tidbit.
